<subSubSection lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="21" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1770,2013]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,290,1770,1796]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Comments:</emphasis>
Sixteen individuals were sampled, which presents: (1) the ventral region of all tibiae black, as well as the ventral region of the apical half of the femur III, (2) wide wings, with numerous black punctuations; (3) rhomboid fastigium of the vertex, much longer than wide, with a white apex, (4) apex of the fastigium of the vertex coloured as the rest of the body, with a black spot above the fastigium tooth, (5) quadrangular mirror, with all the margins slightly curved, lateral and medial margins much longer than the anterior and posterior margins.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1770,2013]" lastBlockId="20.[151,1436,151,357]" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="21" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,1950,1976]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Bioacoustics</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[362,484,1950,1977]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[210,1381,196,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-17@17.[202,1385,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 7. Calling songs of Copiphorini from the ParNa Iguaçu.A–D: Neoconocephalus rioclarensis; E–H: Neoconocephalus sp. 5.;A and E: sonogram of a sequence of echemes; B and F: sonogram of one and four echemes; C: sonogram of four syllables; G: sonogram of one echeme; D and H: spectrogram of four and two syllables, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6550063" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6550063/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 7E–H</figureCitation>
): Males stridulated during the night, in a long sequence of echemes (superior to seven minutes), that appear in a crescendo of amplitude. When each echeme was analysed, several hemisyllables, also in a crescendo of amplitude, appear. We also highlight that this echemes was regularly spaced. As hemisyllables, sound is just produced by the closing stroke.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,151,357]" box="[199,617,223,249]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis box="[199,427,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Dominant frequency</emphasis>
: 12.1 ± 0.8 kHz.
</paragraph>
